#Nim Deathmantle (#1085): when a nontoken creature dies to my graveyard I may pay {4}
#to return it to the battlefield with the mantle attached (granted pay[[{4}]] + return
#+ rehook). Shock my own bears, pay: they return; the mantle's +2/+2 makes them 4/4 -
#a second shock for 2 leaves them alive, proving the attachment.
[INIT]
firstmain
[PLAYER1]
manapool:{4}{R}{R}
inplay:nim deathmantle,grizzly bears
hand:shock,shock
[PLAYER2]
[DO]
shock
grizzly bears
goto firstmain
goto firstmain
choice 0
goto firstmain
goto firstmain
shock
grizzly bears
goto firstmain
goto firstmain
[ASSERT]
FIRSTMAIN
[PLAYER1]
inplay:nim deathmantle,grizzly bears
graveyard:shock,shock
[PLAYER2]
[END]
#PARKED (.disabled): the pay[[ ]] wedge mechanism, mapped precisely:
#  - pay[[ inside a line is handled by an EARLY STRIP (MTGAbility.cpp ~2468) that
#    moves the follow-up effect into AbilityFactory::storedPayString, plus a LEAF
#    (~3425) that builds GenericPaidAbility(cost, storedPayString). Both must run in
#    the SAME factory pass - that's how spell-resolution cards (Spell Rupture,
#    counter-unless-pay family) work: the nested transforms(( text is hijacked by
#    the leaf at parse time, by design.
#  - TRIGGER-granted pay abilities (this card, Fade Away) re-parse their stored
#    newability text at FIRE time in a FRESH factory: storedPayString is empty, so
#    GenericPaidAbility resolves with no follow-up - pay menu appears, pays, does
#    nothing. (A naive nesting guard mirrors pay( but CRASHES Spell Rupture - the
#    same-pass hijack is load-bearing; reverted.)
#  - REAL FIX: make the stripped follow-up travel with the stored ability text
#    (re-embed into the newability string instead of the factory member), or make
#    the leaf fall back to parsing its own trailing text when storedPayString is
#    empty at fire time.
